<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870819-0116 </DOCNO><HL> REVIEW andamp; OUTLOOK (Editorial) -- Asides:Scorched Earth</HL><DD> 08/19/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> EUROP FREST </IN><TEXT>   The suicide of Nazi leader Rudolf Hess at Spandau prison ended one of the last Soviet toeholds in West Berlin. The Soviets wanted to leave the prison intact after Hess's death as a symbol of World War II. That also would have allowed Soviet military guards to continue being stationed there. But the Western allies moved so quickly the Soviets had no excuse to stay on. Within minutes of Hess's death the German staff was sent home and the moving vans called. The prison will be demolished within two weeks and replaced with that ultimate symbol of capitalism -- a shopping center. </TEXT></DOC>